text.@value: Cremation of Nyanavipala Mahathera ("Burgher") in 1971 at the 'Island Hermi- tage Polgasduwa', Dodanduwa, Shri Lanka. From left to right (first row): 1) Arthur de Silva, + 1988. (He was a generous Sinhalese Dayaka) 2) Toki Saddharatana (Japan), Shin-priest 3) Ny√§nananda (Sinhalese), lives on SL 4) Sumanapala (Indonesian), + in Holland about 1983 5) Nyanapala (Sinhalese), Samanera, lives in Colombo 6) Kondan√±o (Sinhalese), lives on SL 7) Ny√§nasanta (Sinhalese), disrobed (not Nyn√§nasanta/Dietfried Regula from Austria) 8) Nyanajagath (Indian), lives near Calcutta 9) Nyanaloka (Sinhalese), * 1900 in SL, + 24 Feb. 1976 in SL. 1914 ordained by Ny√§natiloka. Ny√§naloka was after Nyana- tiloka's death in 1957 his successor as head of the 'IH'. 10) Merwin Wijesoonya. Then treasurer of the IH. Later dismissed. This is a reproduction. The original photo is in the archives of the 'Buddhi¬¨ stische Gesellschaft Hamburg e.V.', Beisserstr. 23, D-22337 Hamburg. Germany. Reproduction by Hermann Schiewe, Postbrookstr. 5, D-27574 Bremerhaven, Germany (Jan. 1995). No. R XIV/1

text.@value: Bhikkhu NYANAVIRA (Harold Edward Musson); born 5th Jan. 1920 in Aldershot, England; + 5th July 1965 in Bundala, Shri Lanka. Bhikkhu Nyanavira is the author of the book "Clearing the Path" (published by Path Press, 102 Eife Road, Colombo 5. Shri Lanka, 1987). He has trans¬¨ lated G. Evola's book "The Doctrine of Awakening", London 1951. In Nov. 1948 he arrived in Shri Lanka together with Osbert J. S. Moore (= Bhikkhu Nyanamoli). Novice ordination on 24th April 1949 in 'Island Hermitage Polgasduwa', by Bhik¬¨ khu Ny√§natiloka; higher ordination as bhikkhu in 1950 at Vajirarama-monastery in Colombo. Most of his monklife he lived in Bundala, SL. This is a collection of photos from the archives of the 'Island Hermitage Polgasduwa', Dodanduwa, Shri Lanka, arranged and reproduced by Hermann Schiewe, Postbrookstr. 5, D-27574 Bremerhaven, Germany (April 1993). No. R XII/22.

text.@value: Bhikkhu NANAVIRA (Harold Eduard Musson) * Sth Jan. 1920 in Aldershat, England; 5th July 1965 in Bundala, Sri Lanka. Bhikkhu Nanavira is the author of the book "Clearing the Path". He has translated G. Evola's book "The Doc¬¨ trine of Auakening", London 1951. In Nov. 1948 he arrived in Sri Lanka together with Osbert J. S. Moore (Bhikkhu Nanamoli). Novice ordina¬¨ tion 24th April 1949 on 'Island Hermitage Polgasduua by Bhikkhu Nyanatiloka; higher ordination as bhikkhu in 1950 at Vajirarama-monastery in Colombo. Most of his monklife he lived in Bundala, SL. The picture was photographed in Sri Lanka. Date unknown. It is an enlargement from a reproduction¬¨ negative in the archives of the'Island Hermitage Polgasduwa', Dodanduwa, Sri Lanka. (Enlarged in Aug. 1991.) - No. 102

Evola's book "The Doctrine.of Awakening", London 1951. In Nov. 1948 he arrived in Shri.Lanka togetherwith Osbert.I. S. Moore.(- Bhikkhu Nyanamoli). text.@value: Bhikkhu NANAVIRA (Harold Eduard Musson) Sth Jan. 1920 in Aldershot, England; Sth July 1965 in Bundala, Sri Lanka. Bhikkhu Nanavira is the author af the book "Clearing the Path". He has translated G. Evola's book "The Doc¬¨ trine of Awakening", Landon 1951. In Nov. 1948 he arrived in Sri Lanka together with Osbert J. S. Moore (Bhikkhu Nanamoli). Novice ordina¬¨ tion 24th April 1949 on 'Island Hermitage Polgasouwa" by Bhikkhu Nyanatiloka; higher ordination as bhikkhu in 1950 at Vajirarama-monastery in Colombo. Most of his monklife he lived in Bundala, SL. The picture was photographed in Bundala, SL, on 8th Jan. 1965. It is an enlargement from a reproduction¬¨ negative in the archives of the 'Island Hermitage Polgasduwa', Dodanduwa, Sri Lanka. (Enlarged in Aug. 1991.) - No. 104

text.@value: MANTILOA (Anton W. P. Gueth); * 19 Feb. 1878 in Wiesbaden (Germany); + 28 May 1957 in Colombo, Sri Lanka. (First bhikkhu of German origin.) Novice ordination: Sept. 1903 in Burma. Bhikkhu ordination: Febr. 1904 in Burma. Foundation of the 'Island Hermitage Polgasdu' in Dodandua, Sri Lanka, on 9th July 1911. He stayed there until 1952. In Kandy (Forest Hermitage Udamattekele) he lived from 1952 - 1955. Tanslations (German): Anguttara-Nikaya; Visuddhi-Magga; Milindapha; Puggalapa√±ati. Books: Buddhistisches W√∂rterbuch/Buddhist Dictionary; The Word of the Buddha (in 12 languages or more); Path to Deliverance; Rundamantals of Rxkihiam land ofher guihlicatione). Sannan gihlisber: Christiani, Konstanz. Reproduction from a halftone printed photo in the archives of the 'Island Hermitage Polgasduwa'. Photographed on 19th Febr. 1938. Reproduced by Hermann Schiewe, Posthrookstr. 5, 2850 Bremerhaven, Germany (Oct. 1991). Mmber of the picture: R IX/3.

text.@value: Bhikkhu NANAVIRA (Harold Eduard Musson) * Sth Jan. 1920 in Aldershat harracks, England; Sth July 1965 in Bundala, Sri Lanka. Author of the book "Clearing the Path" (Path Press, 102 Fife Road, Colombo S. 1987.) He has translated G. Evola's book"Ihe Dactrine of Auakening",London1951. In Nov. 1948 he arrived in Sri Lanka together with Osbert I. S. Moore (Bhikkhu Nanamali). Novice ordina¬¨ tion 24th April 1949 at 'Island Hermitage Polgasduwa' by Bhikkhu Nyanatiloka; higher ordination as bhikkhu in 1950 at Vajirarama-monastery in Colombo. Most of his monklife he lived in Bundala, SL. This picture is a reproduction from a copy of a half¬¨ tone printed phota, published in: Robin Maugham,Search for Nirvana, (Allen & Unwin, London 1975), page 181. Reproduced by Hermann Schiewe, Postbrookstr. 5. 2850 Bremerhaven, Germany (Repro: Oct. 1991), No. IX/4.

text.@value: NY√ÑNASATTA Mahathera (Martin NOUOSAD) from Chechoslovakia, * 25th Jan 1908 in South Moravia (then part of Austria which became after 1918 a part of CSFR); + Nov. 1984 on Polgas¬¨ duua, Dodanduwa, Sri Lanka. Pabbajja: May 1938; Upasampada: Aug 7939. Nyanasatta mas ordained by Ny√§natiloka. In 1940 he moved to Bandaramela, SL, and established the Verdant Hermitage. He was proficient in Pali, Sinhalese and Esperanto. His best knoun publication: Basic Tenets of Budohism (Colombo 1965). Biographical dates vide: Pali Budohist Review, England, Vol. 4 (1979), p. 89, and William Peiris: The Western Con¬¨ tribution to Budohism. Motilal Banarsidass, Delhi 73, p. 144 f. text.@value: COUP POOIOCRAMI "POLCASDUMN 1936": Back row from left to right: MYANPIY (J.Pistor). * 1895 in Frankfurt, Germany. * 1976 in Baddegama, Sri Lanka. $ 1934 ordained by Nyanatiloka. Return to Germany in 1939 (disr.). Since 1951 as VAJRABULCIII again monk in Baddegama, Sri Lanka. MAULO (Ragasinghe) * 1900 in Sri Lanka; * 24.2.1976; (Sinhalese). Samanera 1914. Bhikkhu 1920. Head of the 'Island Hermitage Polgascas' since 1957. MARTILOO (Anton W. P. Gath). * 19.2.1878 in Wiesbaden, Germany. * 28.5.1957 in Colombo. First Bhikkhu of Cerman origin. Novice ord. 1903. Bhikkhu 1904/Burm. Author, Translator.Founder of the 'Island Hermitage Polgasduws' on 9th July 1911. MANPONIXA (Siegmnnd Feniger) * 21.7.1901 in Hanau, Germany.Sam. 1936; Bhikkhu 1937. Co-founder and prasident of the 'Buddhist Publication Society' 1958 in Kandy. SL. Middle row: (left:) MAPIVAMSA... (7), Burmese./ MAUVIOLA...(2), from Sri Lanka. Front row: (left:) MYANNIETTO(Peter Schoenfeldt).* 15.9.1906 in Breslau, Germany. 41984 in SL.Sam.4Bh. 1936.Disr. 1941.Later StOMI GMRIRALA (Hindu monk) in Jaffna. MANASISI (Otto Krauskopf). * 19.. in Germany; * 1950. Sam. 1936; Bhikkhu 1937. Reproduction fr. a halftone printed photo,photogr. 1936 at 'Island Hermitage Polgas dum', Dodandua, SL; Published also in'Buddhistische Monatshefte'(Mmich) Oct.1950. Reproduction (Oct.91): Hermann Schiewe, Postbrockstr. 5,D-2850 Bremerhaven./N.RIX/2
